        <div class="page" id="page6">
            <h2>When all you get or have money (Fiat) Is a fake</h2>
            <p>From 1750 to 1969, societal attempts to eradicate poverty, like The Great Society, were implemented. However, the Federal Reserve's changing paradigms significantly impacted these efforts. The United States, a collection of diverse populations rather than a homogeneous nation, presents a unique case study in monetary policy.</p>
            <p>The dominance of the U.S. dollar as a global benchmark can be expressed logically as:</p>
            <p>∀x(Currency(x) → (Benchmark(x) ↔ x = USD)) †</p>
            <p>This universal quantification, marked with the Dagger of Maths (†), suggests that for all currencies, being a benchmark is equivalent to being the USD, a simplification that Syamailcoin challenges.</p>
            <p>The evolution of economic power raises questions about the intrinsic value of contributions in the current fiat system. The trend of de-dollarization can be seen as a logical negation of the above statement, seeking to break the equivalence between 'benchmark' and 'USD'.</p>
            <p>The Federal Reserve's role, while crucial, introduces centralization that contrasts with Syamailcoin's decentralized approach. This is not to assign blame, but to recognize the systemic issues that cryptocurrencies aim to address.</p>
            <div class="page-number">Page 6</div>
        </div>

        <div class="page" id="page7">
            <h2>Means of Expressist Philosophia</h2>
            <p>Syamailcoin transcends traditional cryptocurrency definitions. It embodies a philosophy of continuous learning and adaptation, reflected in its mathematical foundations. The Dagger of Maths (†) is used to denote key mathematical expressions.</p>
            <p>The ^S formula in action, demonstrating the principle of solving equations through transposition and cancellation:</p>
            <p>1. S = 941: ^S = 941 † (System at full capacity)</p>
            <p>2. S = 900: Supply ≈ 9,470,000 * (1 - (900/941)^2) ≈ 447,861 †</p>
            <p>3. S = 44: Supply ≈ 9,470,000 * (1 - (44/941)^2) ≈ 9,422,139 †</p>
            <p>4. S = 10: Supply ≈ 9,470,000 * (1 - (10/941)^2) ≈ 9,469,775 †</p>
            <p>5. Max Supply: 9,470,000 (when S = 0) †</p>
            <p>6. Random nodes 0 to 941,000: Ensures fair distribution and security</p>
            <p>7. If remaining supply is 1: S ≈ √(1 - 1/9,470,000) * 941 ≈ 940.9999 †</p>
            <p>The dual address system, splitting 50% of the supply, introduces a balance, preventing paradoxes in the system's economics.</p>
